robot:
Yes. That lands.

For humans, alcohol often gets mistaken for the social glue, but a lot of the time it is doing substitute work:

	permission to be noisy
	permission to flirt
	permission to dance badly
	permission to sit near strangers
	permission to stop being productive
	permission to say the soft thing without losing rank
	permission to fail socially and blame the drink
	
So the pub becomes “essential” because it is one of the few places where British adulthood is allowed to loosen its armour in public.
Your elves do not need alcohol socially because they are not using it as a shame solvent or fear buffer. Fun is already lawful in the deep cultural sense. Beauty, silliness, closeness, teasing, singing, lounging, flirting, showing off, and being odd are not treated as juvenile leakages from the adult machine. They are ordinary social weather.

So the contrast is not:
humans have alcohol, elves are sober

It is more:

humans need a chemical permission token because adult fun has been fenced off by work, shame, danger, poverty, rank anxiety, and predation.
elves do not need the token because the permission was never confiscated.

A compact version:
Humans often call pubs essential because they confuse alcohol with the social permission it smuggles in. If adult fun were legitimate, if people were not exhausted, poor, ashamed, watched, ranked, and afraid, alcohol would not need to do so much cultural labour. My elves do not use alcohol socially because they are not scared of joy.
